{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_tango_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492556/1908030601/0385.xml":{"full_text":"dhe Washingion Times\n6\na fe eT.\n4\nPublished Evening and Sunday at\nTHE MUNSEY BUILDING,\n\nPenn. Ave., between 13th and 14th Sts.\nMant York Os. ........coueesse 173 Fifth Ave.\nChicago Office....1710 Commercial Bank Bldg.\nOMICe...cuvurrrreres....JOUrnal Bullding\n\n\n\u2018Daily, one FeAl sessssnsnrsssss+-$3.00\n\u2018Sunday, one year.....c.eeseee---9$2.50\nFRANK A. MUNSEY.\nThe Times is serveed in the city of Wash\nington and District of Columbia by newsboys,\nwho deliver and collect for the paper on\ntheir own ount at the rate of 6 cents a\nweek for the Evening and cents a copy for\nthe Sunday edition.\nEntered at the postoffice at Washington,\nD. C., as second ciass matter,\nFRIDAY, MARCH 6, 1908.\nMake These Schools Fireproof!\nTo James A. Tawney, clair: .an of\n\u2018the House Committee on Appropria\ntions, and William B. Allison, chair\nmnan of the Senate Committee on\n\u2018Appropriations:\n\nOn allowances fixed by your com\narittees, bids are shortly to be\nopened for three school buildings\nin the District of Columbia. One is\n\u2018to house 600 youngsters, and to\n.stand in B street southeast, near\nThirteenth street. Each of the\n\u2018others is to house 800 of our chil\n\u2018dren, one near Howard University,\nthe other in Mt, Pleasant.\nThe specifications are already\npublished. The proposals in reply\nwill be opened in the first instance\ntomorrow, in the second a week\nlater, in the third, perhaps, ten\n\u2018days later still. By no possible\nreading can those specifications be\n\u2018made to promise our children secur\nifty from fire. They provide for\nistairways of slate and iron. Other\nwise they are \u201cfire resisting.\u201d But\nnothing of their special quality as\n\u201cfire resisting\u201d buildings will pro\nitect a single wooden joist from the\n\u2018flames.\nYour committees have allowed\nabout 13 cents a cubic foot for\n\u2018these schools. This is not the time\nto urge that Philadelphia, Boston,\n\u2018Chicago, St. Louis, and New York\n\u2018appropriate 24 to 28 cents a cubic\nfoot for corresponding uses. But\nit is unquestionably the time to\nurge that 17 cents a cubic foot\nwould make all three of these\nbuildings proof against fire to their\nroofs, and that 23 cents a cubic foot\nwould make them fireproof through\nout.\nThe time to act is now. The need\nfs the security of 2,400 little chil\ndren. The responsibility rests on\nyou. In the name of those children\nand their parents, in the sickening\nshadow of the disaster at North\nCollinwood, the people of Washing\nten look to you to do these things\nwithout waiting\u2014\n\nTo begin the construction of fire\nproof schools for the United States\nCapital with these three buildings.\nTo stop by legislation the award\nof contracts for these three build\nings according to the specifications\npublished.\nTo provide the additional sums re\nquired to make them fireproof, at\nleast to the roof.\nAn Artist on America.\nMme. Schumann-Heink, who has\nmany times charmed Washington\naudiences with her beautiful sing\ning, gives the {following reasons\nwhy she is determined to become a\nfullfledged American:\n\n\n\nQeesuse it's the land of opportunity\nfor women and children. It has brought\nme good luck and fortune from the first\nday I set foot on its soil. Americans\npay me more money to sing one night\nat the Manhattan than is paid me for\nweek abroad. I've only sung there\none night so far this season, but 1 will\nderive \u00a3125,000 from my concert tour,\nand\u2014just think of it'--a phgnograph\ncompany gives me $20,000 more to sing\nfuto it. I guess i ought to think pretty\nwell of America, don't you?\nWe do. Anyone who makes $150,\n000 or thereabouts pleasantly and\nhonorably in the course of a season\nlasting eight months ought te think\npretty well of this land of singers\nand singing machines. They pay\nhigher wages by the night down in\nBuencs Aires on some occasions,\nbut they have neither the tours nor\nthe phonograph companies to be\nfound in this country. Nor, in fact,\nhave they the art.\n\n\u201cIt makes me furious,\u201d says the\nfamous contralto, \u201cto hear alleged\ncritics say that America has neither\nart nor conception of it,\nAmerica has splendid art\u2014great,\nbroad, all-absorbing and allconeceiv\ning art\u2014and it's the country\u2019s new\nness and wonderful power of as\nsimilation that has given her these\ntwo splendid virtues.\u201d\nThe performances given in this\ncountry by our American grand\nopera companies are unquestion\nably the finest to be heard in all\nthe world. We have several orches\ntras that rank with the best in ex\nistence. We have schools and art\nists. And we have \u201cknockers,\u201d\n\n\u2018some. of whom are natives and who\nas well as artistry.\nMme. Schumann-Heink is the first\nto acknowledge fairly and squarely\nthat the opportunities for artistic\nsuccess in this, the United Stater,\nare unrivaled, and that if America\npays the highest prices it gets the\nbest results. The severest critics of\nAmerican art have been those who\nfailed. to make good here, or who,\nwhile complaining of American hab\nits, have been eager recipients of\nAmerican dollars.\nThe Improved Business Outlook\nThe Bank of England yesterday\nreduced its dis\u00a2ount rate to 31; per\ncent. Following the New York bank\nflurry of October that rate rose\nrapidly to 7 per cent, and has been\nfalling ever since. The explanation\nof it is simple: English bankers are\nnow fairly in the position in which\nAmerican bankers will be very\nsoon: they have more money than\nuse for it.\nRight now the country has more\nmoney than business. That is al\n\nways the case immediately follow\ning the resumption of confidence\nafter a financial depression. But\nbusiness, stimulated by the easing\nof money, is resuming rapidly. The\nprogressive cheapening of money in\nEngland is being felt here, and will\nbe felt still more.\nThe very best information which\nis to be had in finaneial and Govern\nment circles indicates that resump\ntion is going to be faster than ever\nbefore was known following a pe\nriod of severe depression. True,\nmanufacturers will be sl wer about\nresuming at full blast than they\nwere about shutting down or eur.\ntailing operations when the money\ni\n\n\ntrouble struck them. Likewise rail\nroads will find transportation\nslower in picking up than it was in\ndropping off. But the restoration\nof normal conditions is making ex\ncellent progress, and under the\nstimulus of cheaper money will pro\nceed still faster.\n\n\ni\n\nThe chief thing that assvres quick\n\u2018recuperation at this time is the big\n\u2018demand for American agricultural\nproduets, and the outlook for a\nlarge crop this year. The edge has\nbeen taken off the business troubles\nby reasou: of the immense move\nment of these products. With a\ngood ercp outlook still contivuing,\na month hence there can be little\ndoubt that tremendous -trides will\nhave been made toward restoration\nof the commercial conditions which\nprevailed before the flurry of Oe\ntober.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\ni\nFinancial folks are really blaming\nmore things on the Hepburn law than\nis fair. Recently the Gould systema has\nplaced two ef its subsidiary lines in\nthe hands of receivers, one in the far\nSouthwest, the other in Maryland; one\na coal railroad, the other a frontier\nline; both doing good business, and,\napparently, in mo prospect of trouble.\nIn each case railroad legislation was\nblamed. In neither case is railroad leg\nislation believed, by anybody at all in\nformed, to have been in any wise re\nsponsible.\n\n\n\nMr. Bryan's platform sounds wonder\nfully like Theodore Roosevelt's plat\nform, The only matter left open for\nargument seems to be the old question\nof who saw it first.\ni\n\nA Pennsylvania man, in his will, made\na bequest of his soul. He's in luck, if\nafter a long life in this vale of tears\nhe was still in such unquestioned pos\nsession as to be able to bequeath it.\n4\nSympathy is due the Czar if there are\nmany more like that Chicago anarchist\nin his dominions.\n\nHas liberty perished in Switzerland?\nThat republic, the home of freedom,\nrecently kicked beyond its borders a few\nrash Mormon missionaries.\n\nThe hatpin continues to be the most\neffective weapon of warfare, Almost\nevery day brings new testimony to its\neffectiveness. It is modestly suggested\nthat a trained hatpin corps would repre\nsent vastly better investment than any\nmore submarines,\n\ni\ni\n\nThe milliners are already getting\nready to frame up the Easter bonnets,\nand the same old jokes are Leng dusted\noff.\n\nWhat has become of the ancient Pop\nparty\u2014is Tom Watson the sole rempant?\n\nCounty Chairman Herbert Parsons is\nsending out offers of flower seeds to his\nconstituents, along with the announce\nment that he is a candidate \u201cor re\nelection, as head of the New York coun\nty committee. Mr. Parscns evidently\nproposes to keep the roof garden vote in\nline, if possible.\n\ni\n\nIt seems as if the number of military\ncecrets which foreign governments are\nspying around to locate in this country,\nis utterly disproportionate to the size\nand consequence of this nation\u2019s military\nestablishment.\n\nThe charges about the Oriental Bank\nof New York suggest that it was run\nby a seer rather than a financier.\nTHE STORY OF STARLIGHT\nAugust Belmont, president of the\nJockey Club, at a dinner in New York,\nsaid of racing:\n\u201cRacing is honestly conducted in the\nmain. The stories that one hears about\nit are rather absurd. They are like the\nstory of Starlight.\n\u201cOnce there was a group of sports\nmen who were all quite broke. They\nmust, however, get in to the races. And\none at a time they presented themselves\nat the paddock gate.\n\u201c\u2018I am the owner of Starlight,\u2019 tha\nfirst said. He was well dressed and im\nposiag. They* believed and passed him\n\ni\n\u2018I am Starlight\u2019s trainer,\u2019 said the\nsecond. His red fsza and bluff manner\nbore out his story, and they admitted\n\nhim,\n\u201cThe third man, small and thin, next\nappeared.\n\u2018Starlight\u2019's jockey,\u201d he sald shortly,\nand hurried through the gate,\n\u201cTne fourth and last man of the\ngroup was very shabby indeed.\n\u2018Well, who are you? they said hn\npatiently, when he presented himself.\n\u201cI am Starlight,\u2019 was the meek\n\nnaa a a\nTOM RONAN, \u201cTHE BOWERY DEPEW,\u201d\nWho Is Here to Demand Higher Pay for New York Custom House Employes.\n\nRe A Y\nTakes General Fling at\nPolitics and Pro\nhibition.\ni Ea\nt\u2014 _\nerrs\ni\nj\n\n\nIE Ss ha\nThinks Roosevelt Will\nBe Elected for a\nThird Term.\n\n\ni\n\ni\n\u201cI told Senaior Depew we Douys on\nthe Bowery had decided that the House\nwas nothing but a lemon grove, and I\ncame to Washington to dicker with the\n\u2018peach orchard\u2019 over on the Senate\nside.\u201d\n\n\ni\n1\nThus spoke Tom Ronan, \u201cThe Bow\nery Depew,\u201d genial Irish politicia. vet\neran of many political campaigns, stel\nlar attraction along the Bowery and\nfriend to everybody, the President in\ncluded, except the \u201cfool temperance\ncranks,\u201d whom he says he consistently\nhates with a hate begot by bitter ex\nperience.\n\n\n\n\nmp\u2014\u2014\n1\n\n\n\nMr. Ronan paced back and formh in\nhis room at the National Hotel, and\nwith short, ter e sentences and expres\nsive gesture, and now and then an ex\npressive adjective that Uucle Joe Can\nnon is said to use to alvantage, ex\nplained that he was in Washington for\na purpose, and intendea to accomplish\nit. He is at present a lobbyist, and\nproud of it. He's trying to get an in\ncrease in wages for the employes of the\nwares department of the New York\ncustom house, and heads a missionary\necammitteas of three\nBut first let it be explained that there\nare other things Mr. Ronan is proud of.\nFirst of all, he glories in the title of\n\u201cThe Bowery Depew.\u201d Again, he de\nlights to have had the honor of wheel\ning a truck down the Bowery many\nyears ago, in order that President\nRoosevelt, then a candidate for gov\n\n\nFebruary\nCirculation Figures\nNet Daily Average:\n\n\u201cExcuse me, miss, if I hurt your feel\nwho were reading the valuable columns\n2 J e u\nof The Times. Harry King.\nThe Times....o. veins; 44,820\nThe Star... cui 38,906\nm\u2014\n\u201cExcuse me- I-I real-ly\u2014d-did\u2014. Ex-|\ncuse me! Then he made a rush\nthe door.\u201d George Norris.\nNew Hampshire avenue and Randolph\n*Circulation for February 29 esti\nmata\nstreet northwest.\n\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, FRIDAY, MARCH 6, 1908.\n\u201cTHE BOWERY DEPEW\u201d SCORES\n\u00ab$7200 BUNCH ON THE HILL\u201d\nIN OWN QUAINT PHILOSOPHY\np14\n17\nTL\na 7\nATR, z\n5 3 fr\npe W Z 75\n3 ie\nA}\n3 YL)\nit 118 3) L(A)\ni oul\n[1 LR\nRA\niim\nLF\n4\ni! f f\n1 i\nseas 4 El J\nN J\nJ\n1 i\nL SY \u201cih yy p\nNl\n\n\nMuch to Be Proud Of.\nA Bunch of Epigrams\nBy \u201cThe Bowery Depew\u2122\ni i\n\u201cf believe in barrooms, but not in\naffinities. New York is ahead of\nme there.\n\nS\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 2\n\u201cI know seventeen Congressmen\nwell enough to borrow money. That's\na pretty close acquaintance.\n\n\u201cThe Bowery thinks the House is\nnothing but a lemon grove. It's go\ning to tr; the Senate's peach or\nhard.\n\n\u201cCongress ought to be paid by the\npiece or made to work ten hours a\nday.\n\u201cHooker Washington says piohibi\ntion is good for the colored man. I\nguess S80. A negro is like a Dem\ncrat; he doesn\u2019t know w'on he's\n\u2018had enough. All negroes wiil soon\n\u2018be Democrats.\u201d\nernor, might make a stump speech,\n\u00ab1d of elubbing a policeman because he\ndig: t keep order right near the im\nprovisgd platform. He is distinguished,\nfurchermore, because he first called\nSenator Depew \u2018\u2018a peach\u201d in introduec\ning him to a Bowery audience. Once\nmore he delights because he\u2019s about\nthe only Republican in Tim  Sulli\nvan\u2019s Second Assembly District, and is\nyet a friend to the Lemocratic Tim.\nNow for the interview. You have to\nhear Mr. Ronan and see his smile to\nproperly appreciate it, but, anyway,\nhe's as versati.e as they make them.\nand refuses to talk on any one subject\nJaore than a minute at a time. The\ncare of children, the running of the\nSenate, and vrohibition in Arabia wore\nall handled in the same epigrammatic\nstyle, and with lightninglike rapidity.\n\nPresident Same Fellow.\n\u201clI saw the President yesterday,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cHe's the same fellow he was\nyears ago whew 1 heiped him get on\nthat truck. The campaign committee\nwasn't going to let him speak on the\nBowery, but he\u2019d promised me to, and\nhe broke every blanked engagement and\ndid so. It's just that way today. He\ncan\u2019t be bossed; that's wny the people\nare for him. I'll bet every cent I have\nhe has to take apother nomination.\nFA =e a\u2019\nni ltl\n\u201clI asked him yesterday if he remem\nbered that day on the Bowery and Low\nsomebody swiped his scoar when he iaid\nit aside while making his \u2018speech. Of\ncourse he remembered it. He doesn't\nforget anything.\nings, but I did not care to disturb those\n\u201cHughes? No, he won't do. Hed\nmake a bum President. He won't take\nadvice. He's tried to imitate Roose\nvelt without having the ability. He has\nmore whiskers than brains. Taft? Yes,\nmaybe. He'll do if the President re\nfuses. but nobody will run on the Bow\nery like Roosore t.\n\n3344 Prospect avenue northwest,\n\u201cBryan? you ever see a man\nlose tWiee and then get gee Bho\n4 \u201cExcuse my awswardness. I A\nu wo strikes on a man Lhe\noS vainly endeavoring maintain my Knight, of\nSewer Wagon\nCold Comfort\nFer Lawmakers\n3\nME _- A \u2014\u2014\u2014_\u2014\ni i.\nMembers of House Commit\ntee See City Streets\nUnder Difficulties.\nThree members of the House staggered\ninto the rooms of the House Commit\ntee on Appropriations today, called\nioudly for a copy of \u201cFirst Aid to the\nFreezing,\u201d shook several clouds of\nicicles out of their sleeves, and battered\nan innocent thermometer to fragments.\n74 f 4 A 7\noy\n[5 a y=\nThey were Burleson of Texas, Gard\nner of Michigan, and Bowers of Missis\nsippl.\nBowers, in his haste to get to the\nfire, threw the big brass fender over\nthe committee table. But Burleson, who\nis tall and big, and strong, got in\nahead of him, and comfortably en\nsconced himself before the blazing logs\nof the roaring wood fire. The cold had\naffected Gardner's German accent, and\nhe couldn't say a word.\n\ni\nZN =7\nfat N S\n\u201cOh-h-h, I'm so c-c-o0ld!\u201d blubbered\nBurleson.\nThe same sentiment, with trimmings,\nwas blubbered by Bowers.\nGardner, with careful fingers, drew\na long, juicy lecicle out of his collar,\nand gazed at the fire over Burleson's\n-shoulder.\n\n\nRide Not Pleasant.\nAs members of the District subcom\nmittee of the Committee on Approoria\ntions they had been making \u00aba tour\nof Washington, inspecting the streets\nand schools, sc as to see where the\nbalm of money would do the greatest\ngood. They had been accompanied by\nEngineer Commissioner Morrow, who\nhad disappeared. They had left an\norder that a St. Bernard dog, heavily\nladen with restoratives, be sent out to\nlook for him.\n\n\n3\n\n\u201cWhat's the matter?\u2019 the trio was\nasked: \u201cDid you go in a glass-front au\ntomobile?\"\u2019\n\nTo this guestion Burleson made reply\nin language that wag sad, mild and\nreproachful.\n\n\u201c*Automobiie!\u201d\u201d he cried, jumping up\nand down on the blazing logs until a\nstorm of sparks went up the chimney.\n\u201cT'H have you to understand that the\nDistrict government took us on this\ntour in a wagon belonging to the sewer\ndepartment or the engineer department!\nDrawing it was a nag who must have\nseen better days, better weatier, and a\nbett\u00e9r equipage.\ni\n\n\n3\n\n\n\"Automobiles! Not on your life!\u201d\n\n\u2018Net on your life!\u201d echoed Bowers.\nThe Slowest Team.\n\n\u201cThe slowest team I ever was in!\u201d\nwent on Burleson, jarring the whole\nfireplace with his heavy gestures. \u201cThe\nthing crept along. None of us had\nthe nerve to suggest a faster galt. If\nwe had, we would have been liable to\narrest for cruelty to animals. It was\nmiserable\u2014miserable!\"\n\n\ni\nI\n\nTRen the three men tried to decide\nwhy they had been offered the hospi\ntality of the sewer department, as a\nmeans of inspecting the streots. One\nsuggested that as the requests in the\nDistrict bill this session for automobiles\nfor the officials are as thick as au\ntumnai leaves in Vallombrosa th: creak\ning wagon and the groaning nag were\nbrought forth to impress on the com\nwittea the necessity for granting the\nmoney for automobiles.\n\n\n1\n\n\n\n\n\nIt was a matter for peculiar sensa\ntions among the members of the com\nmittee that,\u2018 as thelr turnout was la\nboriously and uncertainly rounding a\nstreet corner, a handsome carriage,\ndrawn by a spirited animal and con\ntaining the president of the Board of\nCommissioners of the District, shot past.\nThe Commissioner smiled kindly, not to\nsay sympathetically.\n\n\na\n\na\n\n\nAfter thawing out, the three legisla\ntors voted unanimously that a tour of\ninspection in a sewer wagon in winter\ntime is not altogether a great and shin\ning joy.\n\n\nities. Hearst? He does some good with\nhis money, but he's just cranky enough\nto run to the bowwows in two months\nanything he touches. It would be the\nsame way with the Government.\nEe I od Ll\nOpposed to Prohibition.\n\u201cTalking about cranks, though. The\nprohibitionists are the the limit. Do you\nknow I never worked for a (en.nerance\ncrank in my life that he didnt beat\nme out of some money oy else pay me\noff on Monday for fear I'l P4v= a good\ndinner Sunday?\n\u201clook at these blanked Arabs and\nother foreigners. They wear their\nfreak clothes and have no barrooms,\nand they are right where they were\n8,000 vears ago. Ain't it so?\n\u201cYes, I believe in bars, but not in\naffinities. My wife and I have been\nseparated twenty-one years, but I don't\nwanf any affinities.\n\u201cNew about this bunch over on the\nHill. They raised their own salaries\nand neglected everybody eclse. We cus\ntemhouse men and other Government\nemployes deserve some consideration.\nI think $7,500 is a big price for most of\nthe lot. They ought to either make them\nwork by the piece of else ten hours a\nday.. Half of them are cut out for\nsomething else. Many a mother has\nmade or tried to make a preacher out\nof a boy who might have made a dandy\nstonecutter.\n\u201cStill, there are some good ones. 1\nknow seventeen Congressmen well\nenough to borow money from them, and\nthat's mighty close acquaintance.\n\u201cDepew is all richt. I don\u2019t pretend\nto be in Depew's circle financially or\nsocially, but he treats me with respect,\nand I treat him likewise, and this is\nwhat counts. That's the President's\nsecret. He's a Harvard graduace, but\nhe's been out West and lived close to\nrature and knows how to handle men.\nIs Writing a Book.\n\u201cSpeaking of college, did vou know\n92 per cent of the men who asked help\nof the Bowery Y. M. C, A. last vear\nwere college graduates? I'm writing\na book on \u2018College Friends I've Met on\nthe Bowery.\" I've been there twenty\none years, you know.\u201d\n\u201cThe Bowery Depew\u201d said a lot of\nother things, all equally as interesting\nand full of philosophy. However. whet\nhe's dreaming about now is that ir\ncrease in w which must come\nthr the \u201c$7,600 bunch or the Hill.\u201d\nHe'll here till Saturday, he says. and\nintends to Bo back with glad tidings.\nWith him are Steve Cooney and J. T.\nMeir, who echp his sentiments.\nRAILWAY GUARD A THIEF;\nEXPLAINS MANY RCBBERIES\nPARIS, March 6.\u2014The robbery of the\nluggage of wealthy Americans touring\nEurope, which has heen reported from\ntime to time for the last six montte,\nhas heen explained by the arrest and\nconfession of a guard on the Paris\nRiviera line at Marseilles,\nThe guard was possessed of a bunch\nof skeieton keys, and when alone in\nthe baggage car would rifie trunks of\nwhat he Sosed. Many thefts 9 valu\nable jewelry have a report to the\nofficials \u00a2f the road\nI= eS ES 2 ES i wa Vie hy a Bh a I i x\nWHAT DID HE SAY?\n[F YOU CAN IMAGINE\nYOU WILL GET $5.00\nE 3\n\n\nPr Re\nhd\n\nee.\nyd g\nBily Heavywaitt crushed Miss Svelte\u2019s tiny foot in\na crowded F street car. The poor girl suffered agonies,\nyet she lai:ghed heartily at his remark.\nFe\n7 ill\nWhat did he say?\nThinlz it over. What DID hz say?\nSend your answer to the Question Editor, Washing\nton Times. The person submitting the best answer will\nreceive five dollars. The answer may be from one to\ntwenty-five words. All replies MUST be written on\npostal cards ard contain full name and address of sender.\nAnswers will be accepted until 6 o'clock Saturday aiter\nnoon, and the name of the person submitting the best\nreply will be published in The Sunday Times.\nThat readers of ir'2 1imes are gener\nally interested in Billy's blunder, and\nwhat he might have said is attested by\nthe hundreds of answers that every mail\nbrings to the office. Here are a few\nthat came this morning:\n\n\u201c1 beg ten thousand pardons. I was\nso intent on looking at your pretty face\nand stylish hat, that 1 did not see your\ntiny little foot, Teddy Tucker,\n29 U stre\u00e9t northwest.\n\u201cExcuse me, madam, your foot is so\nsmall I couldn't see iv\u201d\nCharles Morris.\n614 G street northwest,\nbeg your pardon, miss. Did I step\non your pet corn? Ha, ha!\u201d\nMrs. Mary Johnson,\n330 Delaware avenue northeast,\n\u201cOh! I beg a thousand pardons fair\nmiss; your pretty, shapely foot is s0\ndainty and small, I failed to see it.\nKatie Wood.\ndainty and small, I failed to see it.\u201d\n\u201cExcuse me, but aren't you afraid of\npickpockets, or having Your purse\nsnatched?\u201d Mrs. H. Thornton.\n235 T street northeast,\n\u201cWhy bless vour dear little soul, and\npardon my awkwardness. Your lovely\nlittle foot was so tiny that I mistook it\nfor\u2014well, the fact is, it's so small 1 did\nnot see it at all.\u201d E. D. Tucker.\n29 U street northwest.\n\u201cpardon me, my dear miss; I thought\nthat was a a fly, it was so smail\u201d\nS. E. Golden.\nBallston, va.\n\u201cOh, excuse me' It was so small I\ndid not see it.\" Evalyn Clagett.\n2021 Poriner street northwest\n\u201cPeg pardon, miss. Hope TIT didn\"\nhurt you.\u201d T. Goldshorough.\n142\u00a2 Irving street northwest.\n\u201cReg pardon, madame. but the cars\nare at fau!t. I wouldn't hurt a charm\ning lady with such a pretty foot.\u201d\nJohn C. Tiff.\n1006 H street northwest.\n\u201cWell! I am a masher, (toe) to be\nsure.\u201d Miss E. 8S. Bassett.\n42 Tenth street southeast.\n\u201cBeg pardon miss. Is that artificial?\u201d\nLeslie Clark.\n4i2 A sir-et northwest,\n\u201cPardon a\u00bb, miss, but I believe I\nstepped 0; our fool.\u201d D. A. Cleary.\n45 Rarn\u00e9 \"i road.\n\u201cGreat stars! madam; how could 1\nsee anything as small as your foot?\u201d\nMiss Mary Suliivan.\n\u201cPardon me, miss, but I had a terrible\ndream while standing here; dreamt this\ncar went direct te Union Station. Gee,\nI'li miss my train, G. Sigmund.\n1920 Pennsylvania avenue northwest,\n\u201cMy dear lady, did my shoe hurt your\nfoot? I am sorry for myself. Will you\niel me see where it hurts?\u201d\nEdith Warren.\n1216 Tenth street northwest.\n\u201c1 beg vour pardon, but I don\u2019t think\nit hurt much, as 1 only weigh fifty\npounds.\u201d James Monnell, jr.\n2128 First street northwest.\n*I beg your pardon, miss, dil I make\nyou see stars?\u2019 Mabel Statter.\n117 First street southwest.\nTM Seat\nMiss T{foward.\n612 Eleventh street northeast.\n\u201cBeg pardon, Miss, but if those clumsy\nfellows were