rell,\n1406 Third street northwest.\n\u201cPardon me, miss, I believe I have\nmade a serious mash have I not?\u201d\nMrs. B. Bonnabee.\n505 Second street northwest.\n\u201cMy hat is off, miss, to the tiniest\nfoot it has ever been my fortune to\ntread on.\u2019 D. B. Reagan.\n803 Fourth street northwest.\n\u201cWell, I hope \u2018I've made a good im\npression.\u201d Annie Werdig.\nPer Ninth street northwest,\n\u201cPardon me, miss, but I fear my\navoirdupcis has been to ygu a troy (try)\nweight.\u201d D. B. Reagan.\n8053 Fourth street northwest,\n\u201cPardon me, miss, but these cars are\nso beastly crowded that it is hard for\nus \u2018gallants\u2019 to keep our balance.\u201d\nCarlton E, Lowe,\n72% Sixth street northeast.\n\u201cOh Mrs. J. J. Ferguson.\n329 F street northeast.\nGES WILL COME,\nSAYS SPEAKER CANNON\nSpeaker Cannon is an optimist, as was\nevidenced by his address at the banquet\nwhich marked the close of the six\nteenth annual meeting of the National\nLumber Dealers\u2019 Association in the\nNew Willard Hotel last night.\nWhile believing in the preservation of\ntimber, coal, and iron, the Speaker de\nclared that when the present natural\nresources are exhausted others will take\ntheir places.\n\u201cDo you want us to freeze and live\nin the open that our grandchildren may\nkeep warm?\u201d he asked. \u201cI am sure thag\nother natural resources, aided by in\nventive genius, will take care of the\nfuture.\u201d\nSenator P. Knox of Pennsylvania\nand Representative Jacob Sloat Fassett\nof New York also made addresses re\nlating to the lumber business.\nAy the meeting yesterday afternoon\nthe following ofiicers and board of trus\ntees for 1908-08 were elected:\nC. H. Prescott, jr., of Cleveland, Ohio,\npresident; G. F. Craig, of Pniladelphia,\nfirst vice president; Robert W. Higbie,\nof New Yurk, second vice president: F.\nW. Cole, of New York, treasurer, and\nO 1 1 vy\nH. Prescott, jr. of Clvannd ome. Ww.\nE. Litchfield, of Boston; \u201d\\WW. W. Kiley\